{"title_page": "Peter Coates", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|       image =\n|  image_size =\n|  birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1938|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Goldenhill]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England\n|  occupation = Owner of ''[[Stoke City F.C.]]''<br>Shareholder of ''[[Bet365]]''\n|    networth = {{gain}} \u00a3750&nbsp;million (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/uk/sport/26820/how-the-english-premier-league-clubs-owners-got-rich|title=Random, Interesting, Amazing Facts - Fun Quizzes and Trivia - Mental Floss|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113010153/http://mentalfloss.com/uk/sport/26820/how-the-english-premier-league-clubs-owners-got-rich|archivedate=13 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|      spouse = Deirdre\n|    children = 4, including [[Denise Coates]] and [[John Coates (businessman)|John Coates]]\n}}\n\n'''Peter Coates''' (born 13 January 1938) is an English businessman, the co-founder of [[Bet365]], and the chairman of [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City Football Club]]. He has been listed as the 25th richest person in British football.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=158338&command=displayContent&sourceNode=158321&contentPK=16129697&moduleName=InternalSearch&formname=sidebarsearch |title=This is Staffordshire \u2013 COATES TAKES HIS PLACE AMONG THE BIG PLAYERS |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He founded Stadia Catering in the 1960s and [[Signal 1|Signal Radio]] in 1983.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\">{{cite book|last=Lowe|first=Simon|title=Stoke City The Modern Era \u2013 A Complete Record|year=2000|publisher=Desert Island Books|isbn=1-874287-39-2}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Coates was born in [[Goldenhill]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], the youngest of 14 children.<ref name=\"The Sentinel\">{{cite web|title=Peter Coates honoured for Stoke City impact|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-15517008-detail/story.html?|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref> His father was a [[miner]] who had a keen interest in [[association football|football]], where they regularly attended [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]'s [[Victoria Ground]].<ref name=\"The Sentinel\"/> Coates signed for the club on amateur terms in the 1950s, but admitted he was \"not quite good enough\" to make it as a professional, instead he went on to play for local non-league sides Goldenhill Wanderers and [[Kidsgrove Athletic F.C.|Kidsgrove Athletic]], he stopped playing football at the age of 23.<ref name=\"The Sentinel\"/>\n\n==Early business dealings==\nCoates left school at age fourteen to work in an office. He served in the [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] for his [[National Service]]. Out of the army he rose to become a regional manager at [[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy restaurants]], before founding Stadia Catering \u2013 a catering firm specialising in servicing football grounds. His company merged with Lindley Catering, and he was the company's chair from 1968 to 2001. He also founded [[Signal 1]] in 1983. He is a former donor to the Labour Party.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/26/labour-donors-assem-allam-peter-coates-breakaway-new-party-jeremy-corbyn</ref>\n\n==Bet365==\n[[Bet365]] was founded in 2000 in a portakabin in Stoke-on-Trent by the Coates family, led by his daughter [[Denise Coates|Denise]].\n\nDenise Coates developed a sports betting platform and trading team to launch the business online in March 2001. The business borrowed \u00a315&nbsp;million from RBS against the family's betting shop estate which had been started by Peter Coates in 1974. Bet365 sold its betting shop chain in 2005 for \u00a340&nbsp;million and paid off its loan to RBS.<ref name=\"A Very Private Practice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |title=A Very Private Practice |accessdate=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406194952/http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |archivedate=6 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBet365 has grown into one of the world's largest online gambling companies with its reported figures to March 2010 showing amounts wagered on sports at \u00a35.4&nbsp;billion, revenues of \u00a3358&nbsp;million, and an operating profit of \u00a3104&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"A Very Private Practice\"/>\n\nPeter Coates holds the position of chairman of Bet365. Denise Coates, joint chief executive, continues to run Bet365 with her brother, John.\n\n==Owner of Stoke City==\n\n===First period (1989\u20131997)===\nIn 1989, Peter Coates became majority [[shareholder]] at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]. He was chairman of Stoke City until 1997 before stepping down. During this period the club were relegated to the old [[Football League Third Division]], were promoted from the now renamed [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] and moved to the [[Britannia Stadium]].<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\nIn 1990 the Stoke City board consisted of six directors and it was agreed that a new share issue was needed, with the majority wanting the supporters to be free to purchase. Following disagreements regarding this share issue, several board members left and the board then consisted of Peter Coates, Keith Humphreys and David Edwards.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\nIn 1997, following poor on pitch performances, he was the subject of protests by the club's [[Fan (person)|fans]] and subsequently stepped down.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/> He remained a majority shareholder, whilst Keith Humphreys was appointed chairman. In 1999, a group of Icelandic businessmen formed a consortium to buy the [[football club]]. The [[consortium]] [[Stoke Holding|Stoke Holding SA]] (financially based in [[Luxembourg]]) paid around \u00a33.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.users.totalise.co.uk/~djandyp/stokecity/stoke_ice.htm |title=The Icelandic Connection |accessdate= 10 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061008090601/http://www.users.totalise.co.uk/~djandyp/stokecity/stoke_ice.htm|archivedate = 8 October 2006}}</ref> The deal was completed on 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\n===Second period (2005\u2013present)===\nIn 2005, Stoke Holding discussed the possibility of selling the club back to Peter Coates. The consortium had planned to get to the club into the [[FA Premier League|Premiership]] within the first five years, but the financial implications had proved more challenging than they anticipated. At this time [[Tony Pulis]] who had become friends with Peter Coates was given a new contract and then [[dismissal (employment)|sacked]] four weeks later. A new manager, [[Johan Boskamp]], was appointed. He remained at the club for one season and then left.\n\nAt the end of the [[2005\u201306 Stoke City F.C. season|2005\u201306]] season Stoke Holding and Peter Coates once again started discussions regarding the sale of the club to the latter. On 23 May 2006, the Coates family through a Bet365 subsidiary company completed the purchase of Stoke City F.C. for \u00a31.7&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/content/articles/2006/05/26/local_tv_archive_coates_back_at_stoke_city_0506_feature.shtml |title= BBC Stoke & Staffordshire \u2013 Coates back at Stoke City's helm  |accessdate= 10 December 2006}}</ref> A further \u00a33.3&nbsp;million was paid to have the Icelandic debts cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stokecityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~832463,00.html |title=Stoke City FC Official Site \u2013 Chairman's Blueprint |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Shortly afterwards, Tony Pulis was reappointed. The [[golden share]]s were also removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stokecityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~867690,00.html |title=Stoke City FC Official Site \u2013 United Strength |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the end of the [[2007\u201308 Stoke City F.C. season|2007\u201308]] season Stoke finished Second in the Championship gaining automatic promotion to the [[Premier League]].\n\nSpeaking at the [[Football Governance Inquiry]] in March 2011, he said: \"I am a Stoke boy, I have supported the club since I was a boy and I have had two comings at Stoke \u2013 an early one in 1985, after which I sold the club to an Icelandic consortium and then bought it back again about five years ago this summer. I bought it back again against my better judgment, in some ways, and my family\u2019s, who all thought I was daft to do it. The club was in a mess at the time and I thought I could help it and do things for it, and I was a bit disappointed with my previous time, and there was a little bit of unfinished business about it and all that sort of thing. But I thought it would be important for the area if the football club were doing well. Stoke was having a difficult time. It has lost the pot banks and the mining industry. I thought that if Stoke could get in the Premier League it would give the place a lift and would be good for it. I think that that has happened, I am pleased to say.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=UNCORRECTED TRANSCRIPT OF ORAL EVIDENCE|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmcumeds/uc792-iii/uc79201.htm|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCoates' father, Leonard was a miner and fought in [[World War I]] with the [[York and Lancaster Regiment]] where he was awarded a [[Military Medal]]. In December 2014 it was announced that Leonard would have a street named after him in [[Stoke-on-Trent]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke City chairman Peter Coates's father among first soldiers to have a street named in his honour|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/8203-Stoke-City-chairman-Peter-Coates-8217-s/story-24984826-detail/story.html?|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=1 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218144356/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/8203-Stoke-City-chairman-Peter-Coates-8217-s/story-24984826-detail/story.html|archive-date=18 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCoates was awarded honorary degrees from [[Staffordshire University]] in 2008, and [[Keele University]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Degree-honour-football-chairman/article-3627739-detail/article.html|title=Stoke City chairman Peter Coates earns honorary degree|last=McInnes|first=Kathie|date=4 June 2011|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=4 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coates, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bookmakers]]\n[[Category:People from Goldenhill]]\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Kidsgrove Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Coates family|Peter]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|       image =\n|  image_size =\n|  birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1938|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Goldenhill]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England\n|  occupation = Owner of ''[[Stoke City F.C.]]''<br>Shareholder of ''[[Bet365]]''\n|    networth = {{gain}} \u00a3750&nbsp;million (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/uk/sport/26820/how-the-english-premier-league-clubs-owners-got-rich|title=Random, Interesting, Amazing Facts - Fun Quizzes and Trivia - Mental Floss|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113010153/http://mentalfloss.com/uk/sport/26820/how-the-english-premier-league-clubs-owners-got-rich|archivedate=13 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|      spouse = Deirdre\n|    children = 4, including [[Denise Coates]] and [[John Coates (businessman)|John Coates]]\n}}\n\n'''Peter Coates''' (born 13 January 1938) is an English businessman, the co-founder of [[Bet365]], and the chairman of [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City Football Club]]. He has been listed as the 25th richest person in British football.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=158338&command=displayContent&sourceNode=158321&contentPK=16129697&moduleName=InternalSearch&formname=sidebarsearch |title=This is Staffordshire \u2013 COATES TAKES HIS PLACE AMONG THE BIG PLAYERS |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He founded Stadia Catering in the 1960s and [[Signal 1|Signal Radio]] in 1983.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\">{{cite book|last=Lowe|first=Simon|title=Stoke City The Modern Era \u2013 A Complete Record|year=2000|publisher=Desert Island Books|isbn=1-874287-39-2}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPeter Coates was born in [[Goldenhill]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], the youngest of 14 children.<ref name=\"The Sentinel\">{{cite web|title=Peter Coates honoured for Stoke City impact|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-15517008-detail/story.html?|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref> His father was a [[miner]] who had a keen interest in [[association football|football]], where they regularly attended [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]'s [[Victoria Ground]].<ref name=\"The Sentinel\"/> Coates signed for the club on amateur terms in the 1950s, but admitted he was \"not quite good enough\" to make it as a professional, instead he went on to play for local non-league sides Goldenhill Wanderers and [[Kidsgrove Athletic F.C.|Kidsgrove Athletic]], he stopped playing football at the age of 23.<ref name=\"The Sentinel\"/>\n\n==Early business dealings==\nCoates left school at age fourteen to work in an office. He served in the [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] for his [[National Service]]. Out of the army he rose to become a regional manager at [[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy restaurants]], before founding Stadia Catering \u2013 a catering firm specialising in servicing football grounds. His company merged with Lindley Catering, and he was the company's chair from 1968 to 2001. He also founded [[Signal 1]] in 1983.\n\n==Bet365==\n[[Bet365]] was founded in 2000 in a portakabin in Stoke-on-Trent by the Coates family, led by his daughter [[Denise Coates|Denise]].\n\nDenise Coates developed a sports betting platform and trading team to launch the business online in March 2001. The business borrowed \u00a315&nbsp;million from RBS against the family's betting shop estate which had been started by Peter Coates in 1974. Bet365 sold its betting shop chain in 2005 for \u00a340&nbsp;million and paid off its loan to RBS.<ref name=\"A Very Private Practice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |title=A Very Private Practice |accessdate=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406194952/http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |archivedate=6 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBet365 has grown into one of the world's largest online gambling companies with its reported figures to March 2010 showing amounts wagered on sports at \u00a35.4&nbsp;billion, revenues of \u00a3358&nbsp;million, and an operating profit of \u00a3104&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"A Very Private Practice\"/>\n\nPeter Coates holds the position of chairman of Bet365. Denise Coates, joint chief executive, continues to run Bet365 with her brother, John.\n\n==Owner of Stoke City==\n\n===First period (1989\u20131997)===\nIn 1989, Peter Coates became majority [[shareholder]] at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]. He was chairman of Stoke City until 1997 before stepping down. During this period the club were relegated to the old [[Football League Third Division]], were promoted from the now renamed [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] and moved to the [[Britannia Stadium]].<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\nIn 1990 the Stoke City board consisted of six directors and it was agreed that a new share issue was needed, with the majority wanting the supporters to be free to purchase. Following disagreements regarding this share issue, several board members left and the board then consisted of Peter Coates, Keith Humphreys and David Edwards.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\nIn 1997, following poor on pitch performances, he was the subject of protests by the club's [[Fan (person)|fans]] and subsequently stepped down.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/> He remained a majority shareholder, whilst Keith Humphreys was appointed chairman. In 1999, a group of Icelandic businessmen formed a consortium to buy the [[football club]]. The [[consortium]] [[Stoke Holding|Stoke Holding SA]] (financially based in [[Luxembourg]]) paid around \u00a33.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.users.totalise.co.uk/~djandyp/stokecity/stoke_ice.htm |title=The Icelandic Connection |accessdate= 10 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061008090601/http://www.users.totalise.co.uk/~djandyp/stokecity/stoke_ice.htm|archivedate = 8 October 2006}}</ref> The deal was completed on 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"Stoke City Modern Era\"/>\n\n===Second period (2005\u2013present)===\nIn 2005, Stoke Holding discussed the possibility of selling the club back to Peter Coates. The consortium had planned to get to the club into the [[FA Premier League|Premiership]] within the first five years, but the financial implications had proved more challenging than they anticipated. At this time [[Tony Pulis]] who had become friends with Peter Coates was given a new contract and then [[dismissal (employment)|sacked]] four weeks later. A new manager, [[Johan Boskamp]], was appointed. He remained at the club for one season and then left.\n\nAt the end of the [[2005\u201306 Stoke City F.C. season|2005\u201306]] season Stoke Holding and Peter Coates once again started discussions regarding the sale of the club to the latter. On 23 May 2006, the Coates family through a Bet365 subsidiary company completed the purchase of Stoke City F.C. for \u00a31.7&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/content/articles/2006/05/26/local_tv_archive_coates_back_at_stoke_city_0506_feature.shtml |title= BBC Stoke & Staffordshire \u2013 Coates back at Stoke City's helm  |accessdate= 10 December 2006}}</ref> A further \u00a33.3&nbsp;million was paid to have the Icelandic debts cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stokecityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~832463,00.html |title=Stoke City FC Official Site \u2013 Chairman's Blueprint |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Shortly afterwards, Tony Pulis was reappointed. The [[golden share]]s were also removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stokecityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10310~867690,00.html |title=Stoke City FC Official Site \u2013 United Strength |accessdate=10 December 2006 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the end of the [[2007\u201308 Stoke City F.C. season|2007\u201308]] season Stoke finished Second in the Championship gaining automatic promotion to the [[Premier League]].\n\nSpeaking at the [[Football Governance Inquiry]] in March 2011, he said: \"I am a Stoke boy, I have supported the club since I was a boy and I have had two comings at Stoke \u2013 an early one in 1985, after which I sold the club to an Icelandic consortium and then bought it back again about five years ago this summer. I bought it back again against my better judgment, in some ways, and my family\u2019s, who all thought I was daft to do it. The club was in a mess at the time and I thought I could help it and do things for it, and I was a bit disappointed with my previous time, and there was a little bit of unfinished business about it and all that sort of thing. But I thought it would be important for the area if the football club were doing well. Stoke was having a difficult time. It has lost the pot banks and the mining industry. I thought that if Stoke could get in the Premier League it would give the place a lift and would be good for it. I think that that has happened, I am pleased to say.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=UNCORRECTED TRANSCRIPT OF ORAL EVIDENCE|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmselect/cmcumeds/uc792-iii/uc79201.htm|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCoates' father, Leonard was a miner and fought in [[World War I]] with the [[York and Lancaster Regiment]] where he was awarded a [[Military Medal]]. In December 2014 it was announced that Leonard would have a street named after him in [[Stoke-on-Trent]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke City chairman Peter Coates's father among first soldiers to have a street named in his honour|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/8203-Stoke-City-chairman-Peter-Coates-8217-s/story-24984826-detail/story.html?|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=1 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218144356/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/8203-Stoke-City-chairman-Peter-Coates-8217-s/story-24984826-detail/story.html|archive-date=18 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCoates was awarded honorary degrees from [[Staffordshire University]] in 2008, and [[Keele University]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Degree-honour-football-chairman/article-3627739-detail/article.html|title=Stoke City chairman Peter Coates earns honorary degree|last=McInnes|first=Kathie|date=4 June 2011|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=4 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coates, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bookmakers]]\n[[Category:People from Goldenhill]]\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. directors and chairmen]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Kidsgrove Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Coates family|Peter]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Coates"}
